    "narrative": "Today\u2019s slate for **Ghost Ride the WHIP** is anchored by a high-efficiency trio batting in the heart of our lineup: **Vinnie Pasquantino** (76.21), **Mickey Moniak** (75.75), and **Brice Turang** (73.40). **Vinnie Pasquantino** is our strongest overall play against Martin; while there is a 31% risk of rain that warrants a late-afternoon check, his elite platoon advantage and the +17% boost from a favorable SP matchup make him a must-start. **Mickey Moniak** and **Brice Turang** are the primary drivers of our stolen base strategy today, with both benefiting from favorable SP skill metrics and the \"slow delivery\" coefficient that prioritizes their speed profiles against Buehler and Irvin, respectively.\n\nOur most difficult roster decision involved keeping **Kyle Karros** and **Max Muncy** on the bench despite the favorable matchup against the shaky Buehler. **Kyle Karros** was the closest to cracking the starting nine, but his projected production was ultimately suppressed by a bottom-of-the-order penalty and the optimizer\u2019s preference for the higher run-scoring potential of **Tyler Soderstrom**, who boasts a 67.36 efficiency score. Meanwhile, **Jose Caballero** remains a start today despite a lower score (50.32) because the dynamic platoon edge against Matz is too valuable to ignore in a 5x5 format that heavily weights situational efficiency.\n\nWe are keeping a close eye on the \"Lineup Pending\" status for **Dalton Rushing**, **Josh Naylor**, **Alex Freeland**, **Trevor Story**, **Brice Turang**, and **Mickey Moniak**. While we have assumed their positions for this projection, any shifts downward in the order will require an immediate reassessment of their scoring output. **James Wood** is another name to watch; although his raw score (51.59) is tempered by a daunting matchup against the elite Aaron Ashby (2.89 xERA), his stolen base upside against a slower pitcher keeps him in the mix as a necessary risk to maintain our league-leading speed profile.",
